---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../../components/SiteFooter.astro';

const facts = [
  { term: 'Role', detail: 'Senior Engineering Manager, BNPL platform' },
  { term: 'Span', detail: 'From a seven-person team to a first-class Checkout partner' },
  { term: 'Scale', detail: "~$40B in annual platform volume across international markets" },
  {
    term: 'Headline outcomes',
    detail:
      'Maintainer access to Checkout in two quarters · review cycle from two weeks to ship-when-done · $180M incremental TPV from five experiments in one quarter',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="Leading BNPL platform engineering at PayPal — Munad Mahinoor"
  description="A case study in earning a team the right to operate as a first-class engineering partner inside one of PayPal's most critical codebases."
>
  <SiteHeader slot="header" currentPath="/work" />

  <section class="page-intro">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="kicker">Case study 01</p>
      <h1>Leading BNPL platform engineering at PayPal</h1>
      <p class="standfirst">
        When I joined PayPal's Buy-Now-Pay-Later team in 2022, we were seven engineers with an
        ambitious roadmap and no way to ship it. Every change we owned ran through PayPal
        Checkout, and we had no standing there. This is how I turned a dependent team into a
        first-class engineering partner in one of the company's most critical codebases &mdash;
        and the framework we left behind so other teams could do the same.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider-stripe divider-stripe--muted container-hr" />

  <section class="case-body">
    <div class="container">
      <dl class="facts" aria-label="At a glance">
        {
          facts.map((f) => (
            <div class="facts__row">
              <dt>{f.term}</dt>
              <dd>{f.detail}</dd>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </dl>

      <h2>The blocker</h2>
      <p>
        BNPL was a fast-growing credit business, but structurally it was a passenger. Every
        change we needed to make lived inside PayPal Checkout, and we had no independent
        presence there. Our pull requests sat behind weeks of manual walkthroughs with the
        Checkout team. Prioritization ran on personal relationships rather than any agreed
        process, which meant our roadmap was only ever as fast as the goodwill we could borrow.
      </p>
      <p>
        The real problem wasn't the review queue. It was that no one had defined what my team
        was: what we owned, what we were accountable for, and on what terms we were allowed to
        touch a codebase other people depended on to keep the company running. Until that was
        settled, every delivery conversation would keep collapsing back into a negotiation.
      </p>

      <h2>The give-get</h2>
      <p>
        I started with the politics, not the code. I went to Checkout leadership with a
        deliberately lopsided proposal: we would make no claim on ownership of their codebase,
        their architecture, or their roadmap. In return, I asked them to treat my engineers
        like new Checkout hires &mdash; the same onboarding, the same access, the same ramp-up
        anyone joining their team would get.
      </p>
      <p>
        That framing mattered. I wasn't asking for a shortcut or an exception; I was asking to
        be held to their standard. Alongside it, I formalized my team as the single point of
        accountability for all BNPL changes. If something we shipped broke, the buck stopped
        with us, not with a Checkout engineer who happened to approve the PR. For a team that
        had been treated as a risk to be managed, becoming the clear owner of that risk was the
        thing that made trust possible.
      </p>

      <h2>Earning it</h2>
      <p>
        Access on paper isn't the same as trust in practice, so I structured the next two
        quarters to earn it in the open. I integrated my team into both the BNPL and Checkout
        roadmaps and paired junior engineers as genuine capacity against Checkout's own goals,
        not just ours &mdash; if we wanted to be treated as insiders, we had to carry insider
        work. I built relationships at the staff-engineer level so the technical trust ran
        peer-to-peer and didn't depend on me being in the room.
      </p>
      <p>
        Then I proposed a one-quarter probationary period and asked for the opposite of a light
        touch: I invited extreme scrutiny of everything we shipped. That was the whole point. A
        team that welcomes hard review is a team you stop needing to police. Once we had proven
        the model held, I wrote it up as a repeatable "ladder of trust" &mdash; the concrete
        stages a partner team moves through, from supervised contributions to full maintainer
        standing &mdash; so the next team wouldn't have to reinvent the path we'd walked.
      </p>

      <h2>What it produced</h2>
      <p>
        Within two quarters my team held maintainer access and the L2 designation for all BNPL
        production issues &mdash; we owned our own incidents end to end. The review cycle went
        from a two-week walkthrough to ship-when-done, which roughly doubled our project output
        inside Checkout. The quarter after full integration, we shipped five experiments that
        generated nearly $180M in additional total payment volume.
      </p>
      <p>
        The innersource model outgrew my team. The onboarding program we owned grew the
        Checkout contributor roster to twenty engineers across multiple teams, run as a
        quarterly intake. The following year, my team was named a critical partner on PayPal's
        full Checkout overhaul spanning the entire credit portfolio &mdash; the clearest signal
        that we'd stopped being a team that needed permission and become one the platform
        planned around.
      </p>

      <h2>Scaling the team behind it</h2>
      <p>
        All of this ran on a team I built from scratch, fully remote, in the years after the
        pandemic. I grew it from ten to twenty-six engineers using a pod model &mdash; three to
        four engineers and a lead per pod &mdash; and leaned on Tuckman's forming-storming-
        norming-performing stages to be honest with myself about where each pod actually was
        rather than where the org chart said it should be. Pods demoed culture wins alongside
        delivery wins, because a team that only ever measures shipped tickets quietly stops
        investing in how it works. The product org later mirrored the same pod structure across
        two of its verticals, and I promoted one of my strongest tech leads into an engineering
        manager role.
      </p>

      <h2>What I'd tell another EM</h2>
      <p>
        The instinct when your team is blocked is to escalate the blocker. What actually worked
        was the opposite: I gave up every claim I didn't need, took on more accountability than
        anyone asked for, and invited the scrutiny most people spend their energy avoiding.
        Trust in a shared codebase isn't granted by leadership and it isn't won in a
        negotiation &mdash; it's earned in public, on someone else's standard, and then written
        down so the next team doesn't have to earn it from zero.
      </p>

      <p class="back-link">
        <a href="/work">Back to selected work</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <SiteFooter slot="footer" />
</Base>

<style>
  .page-intro {
    padding-block: var(--space-5) var(--space-3);
  }
  .standfirst {
    font-size: var(--fs-subhead);
    line-height: var(--leading-heading);
    color: var(--color-muted);
    max-width: var(--measure);
    margin-top: var(--space-2);
  }

  .container-hr {
    max-width: var(--container);
    margin-inline: auto;
    margin-block: var(--space-3);
  }

  .case-body {
    padding-block: var(--space-2) var(--space-7);
  }
  .case-body h2 {
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
  }
  .case-body p {
    max-width: var(--measure);
  }

  /* At a glance facts block — semantic definition list, not a layout table. */
  .facts {
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-5);
    padding: 0;
    max-width: var(--measure);
    border-top: var(--border-hair) solid var(--color-rule-faint);
  }
  .facts__row {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: minmax(8rem, 12rem) 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-2) var(--space-3);
    padding-block: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: var(--border-hair) solid var(--color-rule-faint);
  }
  .facts dt {
    font-size: var(--fs-14);
    font-weight: var(--fw-bold);
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-wide);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-muted);
    margin: 0;
  }
  .facts dd {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--color-ink);
  }
  @media (max-width: 34rem) {
    .facts__row {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: var(--space-1);
    }
  }

  .back-link {
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
    font-size: var(--fs-16);
    font-weight: var(--fw-medium);
  }
</style>
